## {{!linkable_header('Course learning objectives')}}

<!-- taken from SIGCse Data Management https://csed.acm.org/knowledge-areas-data-management-dm-sigcse-2022-version/ -->

COMP 421 does not teach how to build a database management system (DBMS)!
It teaches how to use a DBMS and how a DBMS works.


Modular learning objectives:

  - Use relational algebra to describe the relationship between database tables.  
  - Build on your relational algebra skills to construct Structured Query Language (SQL) commands to create, insert, update, and retrieve data in a relational database.  
  - Model enterprise data using E-R models, relational model, and normalization theory to create an database.  
  - Analyze, create and differentiate between the use of indices (B$^+$-trees and hashes).  
  - Demonstrate your knowledge of indices to efficiently sort and join relations.  
  - Demonstrate your understanding of the E-R model, relational model, and normalization theory to create an efficient database.


The material covered in COMP 421 can be broken into three areas of emphasis. The first area includes database foundation material such as the relational model, relational algebra, and E-R model. The second area of emphasis is database application programming and includes among others the topics of Structured Query Language (SQL), integrating databases into programs, web-based database usage, and active databases. The third area of emphasis is the systems side of databases, which includes database indexing, efficient query evaluation, the transaction-based model, concurrency, and security.

COMP 421 also reinforces skills that were learned in early CS classes.
One of those skills is the _iterative development and debugging_ process.
In this course, do **not** expect to immediately code a long SQL query,
get an unexpected response,
and understand what went wrong!
Do **not** fill out an entire B+ Tree, get an error, and expect to understand what is wrong!
You must iteratively develop answers, test their validity, and move to more complex solutions.

This secondary or tertiary skill of iterative development and debugging
is key in most technical skills development.

